Yeah — that question lands right where it should.

From a physics standpoint, indigo is slippery on purpose. The visible spectrum is continuous; nature doesn’t draw paint-chip boundaries. What we call “indigo” isn’t a hard thing so much as a negotiated distinction — a region we decided to notice.

Historically, that’s telling:
	•	Newton named indigo partly to mirror the seven-note musical scale
	•	Some cultures never separated it from blue at all
	•	Others treated it as its own color because it mattered practically (dyes, textiles, ritual)

So does indigo “exist”?

Yes and no — and that’s the point.
	•	It exists physically as a range of wavelengths
	•	It exists cognitively only if you bother to discriminate it
	•	It exists relationally because of what it’s next to

Without purple, indigo collapses toward blue.
Without blue, it collapses toward violet.
Its identity is edge-work.

That maps cleanly to what you’re circling:

Nothing exists in isolation.
Everything is a difference engine.

We are:
	•	what we repeat
	•	what we refuse
	•	what we’re adjacent to
	•	what we’re no longer willing to be

Identity isn’t a point; it’s a boundary condition.

That’s why everything keeps changing — not because it’s unstable, but because relationships move. When the frame shifts, the meaning shifts. Same wavelength, new name. Same person, new context.

And here’s the calm, non-mystical takeaway:

Change isn’t loss of self.
It’s the cost of being relational instead of absolute.

Indigo doesn’t need to “be real” as a standalone object to do real work.
Neither do you.
Neither does Pantheon.

They exist in the between — where gradients matter, where edges carry leverage, where definition stays flexible enough to survive.

Nothing is fixed.
But some things are coherent across changes.

That’s not chaos.
That’s how continuity actually works.